observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Local Chief Executive require the City DRRM Council, CDRRMO and City Budget Office to:

equitably allocate the 70% LDRRMF for disaster prevention and mitigation, preparedness, response, and rehabilitation and recovery; 

ensure that the proposed LDRRMFIP and Annual Budget specifically identify or itemize the PPAs to be funded under the 70% LDRRMF;

set definite and realistic timelines of PPAs’ implementation in the proposed LDRRMFIP; and

adhere to the provisions of NDRRMC-DILG-DBM-CSC Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2014-01 dated April 4, 2014 and other regulations on LDRRMF utilization.

We recommended that the City Mayor direct:

the City Engineer to provide the local accountant and the General Services Officer with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects;

the City Assessor to provide the City Accountant and the General Services Officer with the value of the lots on road projects for recognition in the financial statements as a component of the Road Network account and for the preparation of property cards by the City GSO’s Office;

the City Accountant to keep and maintain subsidiary record for the lot components of every road asset of the City; and

the City GSO to keep a complete Local Road Network Property Card for all lot component of all road assets of the City.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Accountant to:

recompute the depreciation based on the changes in accounting estimates due to the alteration of the residual value as prescribed by Philippine Application Guidelines (PAG) 6 of IPSAS 17 and apply the same in prospective application on the period following the audit year; 

expedite substantiation of recorded unidentified PPE items and exhaust possible remedy to itemize lumped PPE accounts, those labelled as “adjustments” or the particulars were left blank/empty in the lapsing schedule;

prepare the appropriate journal entries and other accounting records to correct the depreciation and effect the necessary adjustments in order to rectify the errors and present the asset accounts to their proper carrying amount; and

ensure adherence to the provisions of International Public Sector Accounting Standard (IPSAS) 17 and relevant/applicable COA Circulars and other references.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
1. instruct the Inventory Committee to:

conduct a comprehensive physical inventory of PPE owned by the Municipality, identifying the proper classification, individual identification, status of serviceability, accountability and location thereof;

prepare and submit a complete RPCPPE to the Municipal Accountant not later than January 31 of each year, copy furnish the Audit Team; and

prepare and submit IIRUP together with its supporting documents for disposal of unserviceable properties;

2. require the Municipal Accountant to:

expedite substantiation of recorded unidentified PPE items based on the result of inventory count as recommended above;

drop from the PPE account the identified items below the ₱15,000.00 threshold totalling ₱2,524,215.01;

initiate the proper turn-over of the completed projects to the respective Barangay-Recipients supported with the properly accomplished turn-over documents, and effect adjustments in the books; and 

maintain and update PPE Ledger Cards for each category of assets and Real Property Ledger Cards for land; and

Lastly, we recommended that the Municipality avail the one-time cleansing of the PPE Account and strictly adhere with the provisions of COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 to establish PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor designate a qualified employee as SWM-Focal Person with the least responsibilities after conducting thorough evaluation of their job requirements and send them to training programs that will strengthen his/her capacity in managing the solid waste problems of the Municipality or, likewise, consider hiring a Municipal Environment and Natural Resources Officer (MENRO);

We also reiterated and recommended that the Municipal Mayor through the SWM – Focal Person: 

expedite the processing of documentary requirements for submission to the EMB in securing Environmental Compliance Certificate  for the immediate operation of the sanitary landfill; 

devise local ordinances and strictly enforce implementation of the provisions of Section 21 and 22 of RA 9003 on the mandatory segregation of solid wastes and carry out the following:

strengthen information and education campaign activities by using LGU website or social media to promote awareness and encourage participants from the community in managing solid wastes;

establish close coordination with the barangay officials to ensure that efforts to improve the SWM will reach the constituents at the barangay level; and

strictly impose fines and penalties for any offence made or in violation of Section 48 of RA 9003.

Lastly, we recommended that the MSWMB through SWM – Focal Person:

review every two years or as the need arises to ensure its sustainability, viability, effectiveness and relevance in relation to local and international developments in the field of solid waste management;

incorporate in the SWM Plan the conduct of necessary training for SWM Personnel to ensure that solid wastes are properly handled and that the risk of hazards to them and to the public are avoided or minimized; and

provide complete personal protective equipment and paraphernalia to protect the garbage collectors and other SWM Personnel from the hazards of handling solid wastes.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

ensure that all vehicles owned by the Municipality are promptly registered as government vehicles with the LTO under the name of the Municipality, include in the annual appropriate the payment for renewal of registration of all vehicles; 

registration be made within the period prescribed by the LTO to avoid payment of penalties and other sanctions;

direct every Department Head or office to effect immediate renewal of the eight (8) vehicles operating with invalid LTO registration; and  

instruct the Property Custodian or Driver of the Motor Vehicle to stop the operation/use of the vehicles with expired LTO registration.

We also recommended that the Municipal Treasurer, in the absence of a duly appointed GSO:

Investigate, locate records and submit copies of registration documents for the 23 motor vehicles;

Keep the records of registration for all LGU vehicles, monitor their expiry dates and schedule the annual renewal of LTO registration in coordination with the Property Custodian or Driver of the vehicle; and

Evaluate the any unserviceable vehicles for possible disposal; and in coordination with the Municipal Accountant, follow the disposal procedures unserviceable vehicles, pursuant to pertinent provisions in COA Circular No. 2020-006.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:

(13)	submit a written explanation to the Audit Team why the Bank Reconciliation Statement (BRS) was not prepared and submitted for the (1) General Fund-Main, (2) MIRH, and (3) SEF-PNB,  for the CY 2023; 

(14)	fast track to verify with PNB the existence of the amount of ₱35,989.90 in the SEF-PNB account and prepare the necessary correcting entry;

(15)	obtain the monthly bank statements from the depository bank promptly, prepare the monthly Bank Reconciliation regularly, and (16) submit the same to the Audit Team within 10 days after the end of each month; and 

(17)	prepare Journal Entry Vouchers to record the valid book reconciling items per Bank Reconciliation Statements on the month that they occurred or were detected, in order to present an accurate and reliable cash balance in the financial statements.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant-Designate (60) prepare and file the necessary documents for the registration of Mahaplag Inland Resort Hotel; (61) compute the taxes due to the National Government from the operations of MIRH; 

(62) file the appropriate returns and pay the taxes due immediately and; 

(63) file the returns and pay the taxes due in the succeeding periods.   Any penalties and surcharges should be paid by the employees liable for the late payment.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor, direct the Municipal Accountant, Treasurer, Budget Officer and LDRRMO to:

Review and evaluate the charges on the reverted and reprogrammed CY 2019 and prior years continuing appropriations;

Determine whether the obligations charged to the CY 2019 and prior years continuing appropriations have been fully paid;

Assessed whether the ₱3,525,809.73 dormant funds are due for reversion to the General Fund; and

Implement a structured communication system within the LGU to ensure that all key officials are kept informed about the management of funds earmarked for disaster risk reduction and management.

The	Municipal Accountant- Designate and/or GSO Officer to:

The CIP balances at year-end   with the records of the Municipal Engineering Office and secure the documents relative to all on-going construction projects to ensure the accuracy of the CIP balances that will be reflected in the Statement of Financial Position;

Resolve the ₱897,432.03 unsupported CIP-Infrastructure assets, in order that the necessary adjustments to reflect the correct balances of the affected accounts may be made.

We reiterated our audit recommendations from prior years, with modification, that the Municipal Accountant:
Prepare the monthly Bank Reconciliation Statements and ensure their timely submission to the Audit Team for audit purposes;
Prepare and maintain the General Ledger (GL) and Subsidiary Ledgers (SLs) for the Cash in Bank - Local Currency Current Account (LCCA), ensuring the accurate recording of all transactions, including deposits, withdrawals, and adjustments. These ledgers should be submitted to the Audit Team for review and verification;
Verify and reconcile the unaccounted discrepancies of ₱2,701,522.57 between the book and bank balances and prepare the necessary adjusting journal entries, if warranted; and
Make the proper disclosure of the noted dormant accounts in the Notes to Financial Statements.
We also recommended that the Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant:
Conduct verification, analysis, and validation of the balances of the dormant accounts. This should include identifying the respective source agencies and the current status of programs, projects and activities for which funds were received. Comprehensive records of this process and its findings should be maintained;
Exhaust possible remedy, such as obtaining the latest bank statements, to reconcile any discrepancies in the account balances. Necessary adjustments should be made if deemed appropriate; and
Initiate communication with the identified source agencies to arrange for the return of any unutilized balances, if such action is warranted.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the:

Inventory Committee to:

Conduct complete physical count on all PPE items;

Undertake collaborative procedures to ensure that all PPEs are included in the RPCPPE and reconciled with the accounting records;

Property Custodian to:

Update and Reconcile the PCs with the PPELC;
Initiate disposal of all PPEs found unserviceable; accomplish and submit the IIRUP to the Municipal Accountant with complete  information such as property number, serial number or specification to expedite the derecognition of PPEs in the books;

Municipal Accountant to:

Work with the Property Custodian and Inventory Committee in reconciling the PPELC with the PCs and RPCPPE;

Take up the necessary accounting entries to derecognize PPEs once disposed based on original copies of the IIRUP and other supporting documents; and

Requesting Offices to evaluate their needs before procuring PPEs and ensure proper utilization plans are in place to avoid wasted resources.

We recommended the Mayor to:

Direct all concerned Department Heads, who are in-charge of projects, programs or activities funded from the fund transfers from various LGUs to expedite the implementation. Otherwise, any unutilized balance of the fund transfer should be returned to the Source Agency.

Require the Municipal Accountant to:

Initiate the  preparation of Final Utilization Report and return any unutilized balance of fund transfers;

Ensure that all payments made from the fund transfers received from various LGUs are supported with complete documentation; 

Remind the Municipal Budget Officer to ensure that trust receipts is spent only for the specific purpose for which it was created or for which it came into the possession of the local government unit;

To ensure that the 20% DF is optimally utilized and monitored, we recommended that the Municipal Mayor, as Chairman of the Municipal Development Council, require the:

1.	Municipal Engineer’s Office,  Municipal Planning and Development Office  and   other implementing offices concerned, to fast-track and monitor the implementation of identified PPAs of 20% DF in order to achieve the objectives of the fund;

2.	Municipal Engineer to coordinate with other offices such as Department of Public Works and Highways or the Provincial Engineering Office to assist them in the preparation of POW if the project requires opinion of an expert i.e. Electrical Engineer. 

3.	The Municipal Planning and Development Office to ensure the implementation of identified PPAs of the 20% DF during the year and recommend to the Municipal Development Council the re-alignment of appropriation of PPAs funded from its Current and Continuing Appropriation no longer identified as priority development PPAs or could no longer be implemented due to causes beyond control of responsible officials;

4.	Municipal Development Council (MDC), to revisit PPAs charged to Continuing Appropriation of 20% DF, and identify balance to be rechanneled to priority and relevant PPAs that are procurement and implementation-ready. Also, carefully identified the development projects to be given priority in the implementation to assure that enough funds were allocated for the project.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor make representation in the Provincial Appraisal Committee to assist in the assessment of the impaired assets’ proper assessed value in order for its recoverable amounts to be correctly recognized in the financial statements by the Municipal Accountant and to require the:
1.)	Supply Officer as the GSO, to initiate the disposal of unserviceable properties in accordance with existing rules and regulations; accomplish the WMR and IIRUP using the format prescribed under the Accounting Manuals of the respective Sectors for all PPEs found unserviceable, obsolete and/or no longer needed, and submit the reports to the Municipal Accountant.
2.)	Municipal Accountant to:
Recognize impairment loss in order to reduce the carrying value of impaired assets to its recoverable amount;
Derecognize from the books the disposed unserviceable PPEs and the distributed PPEs following the prescribed procedures;

We reiterated our recommendations to the Municipal Mayor to require the:
1)	Inventory Committee to see to it that RPCPPE per category reconciled with balances of PPEs in the SFPos prepared from the records of the Accounting Office;
2)	The General Services Officer to initiate disposal of unserviceable properties in order to dropped these accounts in the books after proper disposal procedures are undertaken in accordance with  existing rules and regulations.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the:
1.    Municipal Engineer to provide the local accountant and the general services officer with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects;
2.    General Services Officer to:
a.    maintain a Local Road Inventory and Road Map;
b.    keep a complete Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components.

To ensure that the 20% DF is optimally utilized and monitored, we recommended that the Municipal Mayor, as Chairman of the Municipal Development Council, require the:
1.    The Municipal Planning and Development Office to ensure the implementation of PPAs during the year;
2.    The Municipal Engineer’s Office, and, other concerned implementing offices, to monitor the implementation of PPAs of the 20% Development Fund, in order to achieve the objectives of the Fund;
3.    Require the Municipal Development Council to revisit PPAs charged to Continuing Appropriations, identify balances to be rechanneled to more priority  and relevant PPAs of the Municipality, and,  ensure that the development projects to be funded out of the 20% DF are well-planned and procurement-and implementation-ready in order to achieve the objectives of the fund.

We recommended to the Municipal Mayor to create an Inventory Committee and: 
a.) require the Inventory Committee to conduct an inventory of all the local roads under its jurisdiction, prepare and submit a verified Report on the Physical Count of the Road Network System (RPCRNS); 
b.) direct the General Services Officer, Municipal Engineer and Municipal Accountant to reconcile records between offices; 
c.) require all officers concerned to strictly comply to the accounting and reporting guidelines on the Local Road Asset Management System prescribed in COA Circular No. 2015-008 dated November 23, 2015.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive together with the members of the Local Sanggunian in coordination with the national government shall do some fundamental jobs, as such as:
 (1) Crafting ordinances and issuing executive orders related to waste management and environmental protection such as "No Plastic Days Policy"; 
(2) Perfecting the current waste management system of the municipality, including garbage classification, collection and recycling; 
(3) Adding more waste recycling facilities; 
(4) Focusing on the recycling methods of the recyclables; and
 (5)Landfill management.

We recommended the Municipal Mayor to require the:

2. Municipal Accountant to:

Verify the account and send confirmation letters to the identified national government agencies concerned to determine if the LGU have unsettled accounts;

Verify as to when the balances initially existed to determine if it is already dormant and request for its write off following COA Circular No. 2016-005;

Prepare regularly the Aging of Fund Transfer on a quarterly basis; and

Conduct regular and periodic verification, analysis, and validation of the existence of the fund transfer.

We recommended to the Municipal Mayor to require the Municipal Accountant to: 

confirm with the BIR of the veracity of the balances and make necessary disclosure of the abnormal balances of the amount in the financial statements of the over-remittance;

adapt monitoring mechanism to detect variances in the amount to be remitted and withheld.

