observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
require the Human Resource and Management Officer (HRMO) to -
promptly update the employees’ employment status and salary adjustments in the GSIS Web MSP;
provide updates of employees' employment status to the AAO to facilitate the timely submission of updated information about the agency and its employees to the GSIS;
ensure that the correct premium contributions and loan amortizations are deducted from employees' compensation/salary on time;
require the AAO to –
certify employees' loan applications based on the updated employees’ membership profile and promptly inform the HRMO and City Accountant to ensure timely deduction of monthly loan amortization on the loans certified or approved;
coordinate with the Electronic Remittance File (ERF) Officer to address Reconciliation Billing Issues (RBIs);
require the City Accountant to –
review the unreconciled balance amounting to at least P4,802,881.67 to determine whether the same pertains to balance in arrears or was just a result of error/s in recording to facilitate remittance of the amount due to GSIS or recording of adjustment in the books of accounts, whichever is applicable; and
verify that the monthly premium contributions and loan amortizations due for remittance to GSIS tallies with the amount deducted from the employees’ compensation/salaries in the payroll before the approval of disbursement vouchers for GSIS remittances.

We commended the Local Chief Executive, Municipal Engineer, Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator (MPDC), and other concerned Department Heads for the efforts in ensuring that the PPAs funded under the 20% Development Fund (DF) were well-planned and ready for procurement and implementation. The commitment to developing organized, realistic, and viable PPAs, along with the active facilitation and monitoring of PPA implementation, is highly appreciated;
With regards to the non-implementation of two projects, we recommended the submission of a written explanation and/or justification; and
Finally, we recommended the continuous adherence to the policies and guidelines outlined in the aforementioned Joint Memorandum Circular and other relevant laws, rules, and regulations. Sustained compliance will support the achievement of the municipality’s socio-economic development goals and environmental objectives, ultimately benefiting the constituents of the community.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive instruct the Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the Municipal Treasurer to:
Diligently account for the beginning balance of the Due to BIR account, ensuring that any necessary adjustments or corrections are properly recorded;
Coordinate with the BIR Office to verify the accuracy and/or correctness of the taxes remitted and promptly settle outstanding obligations, if any;
Provide a separate subsidiary ledger for Creditable Value-added Tax and Documentary Stamp Tax for an easy reference and understanding; and
Henceforth, ensure the timely and accurate remittance of all taxes due to the BIR to avoid the imposition of interest charges, in compliance with the applicable laws and prevailing Revenue Regulations issued by the said Office.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the Municipal Accountant in coordination with the Municipal Treasurer to:
Diligently review and account for the GSIS contributions from previous years, ensuring all necessary adjustments or corrections are made, if applicable;
Coordinate with the GSIS Office to verify any outstanding contributions. If unpaid amounts are identified, take prompt action to settle them accordingly;
Reconcile GSIS remittances with the amounts withheld, making necessary adjustments as required to ensure accuracy; and
Henceforth, strictly observe the timely and accurate remittance of GSIS contributions to prevent the accrual of interest, in compliance with applicable laws, rules and regulations.

We reiterated our recommendation that the Municipal Mayor and members of the Municipal Development Council:
stop the practice of including in the AIP some unidentified programs/projects/activities under a lumpsum appropriation; and
identify and include in the AIP specific priority projects which are well-planned and ready for implementation in the current budget year.
We also recommended that the Municipal Accountant Designate:
issue Demand Letters to Barangays with outstanding unliquidated Financial Assistance;
refrain from authorizing the grant of additional FA without first obtaining liquidation report for previously granted FAs;
make the necessary adjusting entry for the FA totaling ₱300,000.00 which was recognized in CY 2024 despite only being granted and released to the barangay in CY 2025;
verify records before issuing Accountant’s certification that funds previously transferred to the Implementing Agency (IA) have been liquidated, post audited and accounted for in the books before signifying in the Disbursement Voucher the propriety and completeness of supporting documents;
furnish the Audit Team with the copies of FURs with complete supporting documents arranged chronologically as reflected in the ledger; and
prepare and maintain subsidiary ledgers for the Due from LGUs account per barangay/recipient of Financial Assistance to support the general ledger balance.

We recommended that Special Disbursing Officers:
stop the practice of transferring their cash advances to other municipal employees;
submit additional supporting documents to validate the actual disbursements charged against their cash advance;
ensure that future cash advances are liquidated with complete and proper documentation; and
refrain from using cash advances to pay for expenses that are required to undertake a proper procurement process.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the HRMO, who also serves as the Municipal Accountant:
mandate the unregistered LGU employees with GSIS and Pag-IBIG to apply for membership to effect remittance of CY 2024 and prior year’s contributions and ensure that employees receive their entitled benefits and avoid unnecessary financial burden.
promptly coordinate with the personnel administering the monthly remittances to update personnel’s employment status and/or salary adjustments in the system. This will ensure that GSIS and Pag-IBIG records reflect accurate and up-to-date information;
coordinate with Pag-IBIG regarding the deficiencies noted in CY 2024 on the remittance of the government share for the employees’ contributions, and remit the amounts due, if warranted;
conduct verification, analysis, and validation of the individual accounts under the Due to GSIS and Pag-IBIG accounts, exhaust possible remedy to reconcile the negative and/or unsubstantiated balances and effect the necessary adjustments, as warranted; and
administer monthly reconciliations of employee premium contributions and loan amortizations by comparing the GSIS and Pag-IBIG billing against the actual payroll deductions and remitted amounts. This ensures billing accuracy, facilitates timely remittances, and guarantees correct salary deductions.

We reiterated our audit recommendations from prior years, with modification, that the Municipal Accountant:
Prepare the monthly Bank Reconciliation Statements and ensure their timely submission to the Audit Team for audit purposes;
Prepare and maintain the General Ledger (GL) and Subsidiary Ledgers (SLs) for the Cash in Bank - Local Currency Current Account (LCCA), ensuring the accurate recording of all transactions, including deposits, withdrawals, and adjustments. These ledgers should be submitted to the Audit Team for review and verification;
Verify and reconcile the unaccounted discrepancies of ₱2,701,522.57 between the book and bank balances and prepare the necessary adjusting journal entries, if warranted; and
Make the proper disclosure of the noted dormant accounts in the Notes to Financial Statements.
We also recommended that the Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant:
Conduct verification, analysis, and validation of the balances of the dormant accounts. This should include identifying the respective source agencies and the current status of programs, projects and activities for which funds were received. Comprehensive records of this process and its findings should be maintained;
Exhaust possible remedy, such as obtaining the latest bank statements, to reconcile any discrepancies in the account balances. Necessary adjustments should be made if deemed appropriate; and
Initiate communication with the identified source agencies to arrange for the return of any unutilized balances, if such action is warranted.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor, as head of the Municipal DRRM Council, together with the Municipal DRRM Officer and Municipal Budget Officer:
Refund the ₱25,590.00 overspent on the procurement of IEC materials and the conduct of IEC-related drills and activities, which exceeded the approved budget;
Submit a written explanation justifying the incurrence of non-disaster related expenditures totaling ₱54,986.00. This is without prejudice to the issuance of Notice of Suspension and/or Disallowance, if warranted;
Implement strict monitoring of LDRRM Fund utilization and disbursements to ensure that they do not exceed the approved budget appropriation; and
Avoid using LDRRM Fund for non-disaster risk reduction and management expenses.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor, Municipal Budget Officer, and the Members of the Local School Board:
Approve Local School Board resolutions for the Special Education Fund Annual and/or Supplemental Budgets in accordance with the timelines prescribed by DepEd-DBM-DILG Joint Circular No. 1, s. 2017;
Ensure that all expenditures charged to the SEF are supported by existing and sufficient appropriation;
Monitor the municipality’s obligations against available appropriations to avoid payments without an approved budget; and
Refund the SEF expenditures amounting to ₱337,103.00 that were incurred prior to the approval of the SEF.

We recommended the Municipal Mayor to enjoin coordination among the department heads concerned to comply with the requirements of COA Circular No. 2015-008, specifically to require the:
Municipal Engineer to:
Provide the Municipal Accountant and the Supply Officer with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for every road project, as well as the report on the repair/ maintenance of each local road network; and
Reconcile with the Municipal Accounting Office the reports on the Local Road Network.
Property Custodian/ Inventory Committee to:
Conduct an inventory of the local roads under the Municipality’s jurisdiction with the assistance of the Municipal Engineering Office; and to prepare the Report on the Physical Count of the Road Network (RPCLRN);
Maintain a Local Road Inventory and Road Map; and
Maintain a complete Local Road Network Property Card (LRNPC) for all roads and its components and reconcile the same with the records of the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Engineer;
Municipal Accountant to:
Maintain the LRNLC for each Local Road Components with complete description;
Reconcile the LRNLC with the Local Road Inventory and Road Map of the Supply Office and Report on Local Road Network of the Municipal Engineering Office;
Provide the correct depreciation for each road component and make the necessary adjustment to correct the understatement of Accumulated Depreciation recognized for the Road Network account; and
Ensure complete disclosure of the total Road Network System in the Notes to the Financial Statements.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:
Prepare adjusting entries to recognize the appropriate Property, Plant and Equipment Account;
Prepare adjusting entries in  the government equity account for the unrecognized expense in CY 2024;
Prepare adjusting entries for the improper debits to the Due to NGAs account for the PPAs which have no FUR submitted to the source agencies; and
Prepare the Fund Utilization Reports for the implemented projects.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:
Establish the correct amount of shares to be remitted to the LGUs/Province and Barangays and ensure the remittance of the same to these agencies;
If after thorough examination of the accounting records there found to be over-remittances, offset the amount of over-remittance from succeeding collections due for remittance to the respective Province and other LGUs;
For the share of Province and other LGUs on the collection of taxes of the Municipality, record the correct amount of Due to LGUs based on the actual collections of taxes to avoid negative balances of Due to LGUs account; and
Prepare adjusting entry for the unrecorded utilization of financial assistance from the Province of Southern Leyte amounting P100,000.00.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the GAD Focal Point System-TWG to:
Clearly identify the gender issues and activities which are attributed to gender and development;
Observe the scheduled GAD Planning and Budgeting as provided by PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA Joint Memorandum Circular (JMC) No. 2013-01, as amended by PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2016-01 dated January 12, 2016 to facilitate timely submission of the GPB and GAD AR to the DILG for review and endorsement;
Undertake gender analysis to identify and confirm existing gender issues ad ensure that the programs, projects and activities are responsive to the said issues; and
Deepen knowledge and build competence on gender mainstreaming, gender analysis, gender responsive planning and budgeting, and GAD related tools, among others through attendance with relevant GAD trainings.

We recommended the Municipal Mayor to enjoin coordination among the department heads concerned to comply with the requirements of COA Circular No. 2015-008, specifically to require the:
Municipal Engineer to:
Provide the Municipal Accountant and the GSO with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for every road project, as well as the report on the repair/maintenance of each local road network;
Reconcile with the Accounting Office the reports on the Local Road Network;
GSO/Inventory Committee to:
Conduct an inventory of the local roads under the Municipality’s jurisdiction with the assistance of the Municipal Engineer; and to prepare the Report on the Physical Count of the Road Network (RPCLRN);
Maintain a Local Road Inventory and Road Map; and
Maintain a complete Local Road Network Property Card (LRNPC) for all roads and its components and reconcile the same with the records of the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Engineer;
Municipal Accountant to:
Maintain the LRNLC for each Local Road Components with complete description;
Reconcile the LRNLC with the Local Road Inventory and Road Map of the GSO and Report on Local Road Network of the Municipal Engineer;
Provide the correct depreciation for each road component and make the necessary adjustment to correct the understatement of Accumulated Depreciation recognized for the Road Network account.
Ensure complete disclosure of the total Road Network System in the Notes to the Financial Statements.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

1.	Direct the Inventory Committee to:

a.	Prepare the Physical Inventory Plan and conduct the physical count of Property, Plant, and Equipment (PPE) in accordance with the procedures prescribed under COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020, to facilitate the proper implementation of the one-time cleansing and reconciliation of the PPE account balances; 

b. 	Ensure the timely preparation and submission of the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant, and Equipment (PPE) to the Audit Team not later than January 31 of each year, and reconcile the results of the report with both accounting and property records.

2.	Require the General Services Officer to:

a. 	Prepare and maintain Property Cards for all PPE items, ensuring accurate documentation of acquisition, description, custody, disposal, and other information about the PPE, based on the source documents of the transactions, and regularly reconcile with the accounting records and the RPCPPE; 

b. 	Prepare and submit to the Disposal Committee the required Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP), listing all PPE identified for disposal;

3.	Require the Municipal Accountant to:

a. 	Prepare and maintain PPE Ledger Cards for each PPE item, with complete details such as acquisition date, description, custody, estimated useful life, rate of depreciation, disposal, and other information about the PPE, based on the source documents of the transactions, and regularly reconcile with the property records and the RPCPPE; and

b. 	Exhaust all possible means to retrieve the necessary data and records (such as acquisition dates, acquisition costs, and useful life) for PPEs acquired prior to CY 2023, and ensure that depreciation is properly recognized.

We recommended the Municipal Mayor to require the Agency Authorized Officer, Alternate Agency Authorized Officer, Municipal Accountant and the Payroll Clerk to:

a. 	Reconcile with the GSIS Office the records and information of all active employees in Calendar Year 2024 such as monthly salaries to update the exact premium contributions to be deducted in the payroll and remitted for the personal share and government share as well as the outstanding loan balances to update the monthly loan amortizations to be paid by the employee;

b. 	Account for the differences among the premium contributions billed by the GSIS and the amount deducted in the payroll and the amount remitted amounting to P152,760.96 and P419,950.46, respectively, as presented in Tables 13 and 14, respectively;

c. 	Account for the difference between the loan amortizations billed by the GSIS, the amount deducted in the payroll and the amount remitted amounting to P157,949.00 and P157,659.36, respectively, as presented in Tables 16 and 17; and

d. 	Henceforth, conduct regular/periodic reconciliation of the premium amounts and loan amortizations to be withheld and remitted with the records of the GSIS Office to avoid under-remittance/over-remittance premium amounts and loan amortizations. The reconciliation of the GSIS accounts of the employees is not a daily activity and neither a year-round activity.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor to direct the Municipal Accountant to:

a. 	Review and reconcile the ending balance recorded in the General Ledger of the Due to BIR account for the taxes withheld with the actual amount remitted to trace the amount of over-remittance and make the necessary adjustments.  Henceforth, conduct regular reconciliation of the balances;

b. 	Adhere to the remittance deadlines prescribed under existing Revenue Regulations, ensuring that all taxes withheld within a given month are fully remitted in the following month;

